        "Abstract": "The goal of visualization is to produce visual representations of complex relationships that would help users efficiently allocate their attention in order to better understand the data. Therefore, there is a need to evaluate and to measure the success of the visualization. This involves examining a number of factors, such as: techniques, methods, use efficiency, effectiveness and user satisfaction. \nEvaluation results are important for all stakeholders. Visual analytics integrators need to know use efficiency, effectiveness and user satisfaction; developers of a system that exploits visual analytics techniques need to know which ones to choose for the problem at hand; users selecting a system, method, or even a parameter setting need information to make the best decision. Furthermore, good evaluation results can help convince integrators and users to adopt novel techniques. Hence, evaluation of visualization is an important ingredient in innovation, from research to development to large-scale adoption. \nEven though the evaluation plays a crucial role in assessment of the quality of the visualization, it remains difficult and has many challengers. Current talk will address those challenges through examples from my research. \n",
