        "Abstract": "Graph perception is a complex process. Much of the perception relies on conventions that seem standard and obvious. One such convention is that, on a graph, numbers increase from the bottom up and from left to right. This left-to-right direction agrees with the left-to-right writing systems used by most of the world's population. However, around 8% of the world uses right-to-left (RTL) scripts such as Arabic and Hebrew. Previous research has shown that  RTL people perceive graphical information differently from their left-to-right (LTR) counterparts. Nevertheless, no empirical study tested how this perception differs when an RTL reader sees a graph.\nHere, we present a study performed with English, Hebrew, and Arabic speakers in which we managed to quantify the RTL effect on visual perception. We also provide some guidelines to mitigate the challenges that we discovered.",
