        "Abstract": "These days, more than ever, the world is converging, and quite a few nations are finding themselves for the first time, dealing with their existence, and their future survival. Several years ago, as part of a research I made in my MA in London college of Communication, I dealt with the identity of nations and how they perpetuate their existence through language and terminology.\n\nHow language is used as a tool in order to define and perpetuate nations. In my research I found four textual platforms: Declaration of independence, Anthems, Propaganda campaigns, and International code - each, with its use of specific phrases, words and terminology, manage to reflect the existence of the nation. Interestingly, in my research, I found out that each of the platforms also accurately expressed a different branding tool, such as: brand values, moto, logo and message. \n\nIn my lecture, I will give a brief overview of my research, and on the work of collecting and analysing the large data I have received in the first platform I have found: \"Declaration of independence\". Fascinating, after covering 30 different declarations, I found that this document holds exactly the same methodology like any commercial brand book, with three parts: the \"why,\" the \"what,\" and \"how.\" \n\nIn my research, using the official translated document that was provided by the nations, I put together all texts of the different 30 declarations of independence in a professional analytic tool to examine their words. I was curious to know how nations have chosen to define themselves: kingdom, state, country, republic, or land? How many times they used positive or negative words in the document, how did they formulate their goals and aims at the moment of declaration: democracy, freedom, rights, etc? Or what was the ratio between the words war and peace, life and death, or God and blood in the texts. \n\nI have summarized my research in one big and heavy book, that was edited like a magazine with 5 major chapters, and various short sections in between, embedded with statistics and infographics.",
